07904nam a22010455i 9781487544355DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875443557 a10.3138/97814875443552doi  a(DE-B1597)618929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04aThe Exclusion of Immigrants from Welfare Programs :bCross-National Analysis and Contemporary Developments /ced. by Edward A. Koning. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (504 p.) :b53 b&w figures, 24 b&w tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tIndex -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tSection One: Setting the Stage -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The IESPI and Descriptive Findings -- tSection Two: Quantitative Analyses -- t3. The Drivers of Exclusion -- t4. Appeasement via Exclusion? Differential Access to Social Programs and Their Effects on Xenophobia, Racism, and Perceived Welfare System Abuse -- t5. Closing the Gaps: The Positive Effects of Welfare Inclusion on Immigrants’ Labour Market Integration -- t6. It Ain’t about the Money: A Cross-Country Study of the Fiscal Implications of Immigrant Exclusion -- tSection Three: Case Studies -- t7. Between Equality and Exclusion: Migrant Integration in Austria’s Bismarckian Welfare System -- t8. Inclusion under Pressure: The Case of Norway -- t9. From Exclusion to More Exclusion: Immigration and Social Welfare Access in the United States -- t10. Why Choose the Inclusionary Path? Social Policy in a Recent Welfare and Immigration Country: The Case of Portugal -- tSection Four: Concluding Reflections -- t11. Welfare and Immigration: Factoring In the Neoliberal Order -- t12. Philosophies of Inclusion and Exclusion -- t13. Conclusions: Is an Inclusive Multicultural Welfare State a Feasible Project? -- tAppendix: Detailed Country Descriptions -- tBibliography -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn light of the increase in cross-border mobility and the recent political climate surrounding immigration-related issues, understanding the politics and policies of immigrants’ access to welfare programs is more relevant than ever. Systematic analysis of this subject has been held back, however, by the lack of a cross-national index of immigrant exclusion from social benefits over time. The Exclusion of Immigrants from Welfare Programs fills this gap by taking advantage of a novel and original measure called the Immigrant Exclusion from Social Programs Index (IESPI), which includes twenty-five indicators regarding immigrants’ access to seven different social programs, for twenty-two countries, at four moments in time. The book includes an assessment of key trends, an investigation of the origins and consequences of variation, and four detailed country case studies of particular theoretical interest: Norway, Austria, Portugal, and the United States. Presenting a cross-national index to facilitate and encourage systematic cross-country comparisons, this book provides insights and data that will allow researchers to probe such questions as the degree to which countries include or exclude immigrants in developing public policies, why some countries are more exclusionary than others, and what the future consequences of this exclusion might be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aethnic relations policy.  aexclusion.  aimmigration.  aintegration.  amulticultural governance.  apolicy differentiation.  apolitical parties.  apolitics of immigration.  apublic opinion.  asocial expenditure.  asocial policy.  awelfare state.1 aBanting, Keith